    "## Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "# Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal of this project was to determine the best neighborhood in Pittsburgh using a data-driven approach. Rather than relying on personal opinions, we used publicly available datasets to evaluate neighborhoods based on measurable factors.\n",
    "\n",
    "As a group, we defined “best” as a combination of safety, housing quality, and economic opportunity. These factors were chosen because they represent key aspects of overall quality of life and can be supported with reliable data.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each group member analyzed a different dataset and created a sub-metric. These sub-metrics were then combined into a single score to rank neighborhoods and determine which one performed the best overall."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "af5868ee-b0fa-416c-a8c6-946272e52d3c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Metrics used \n",
    "\n",
    "To evaluate the neighborhoods, we each combined our metrics into an overall score. Each metric represents a different aspect of what makes each neighborhood \"good\"\n",
    "Safety, which was my metric, was measured by the total number of reported crime incidents in each neighborhood, so fewer crimes meant a better score.\n",
    "Housing was calculated based on high occupancy rates, low vacancy rates, and low forclosure rates. Which suggest how likely people actually want to live in these neighborhoods.\n",
    "Employment was based on how many residents in each neighborhood are employed, which would suggest stronger economic stability from that neighborhood."
   ]
  },
