    "## Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "Through this project, we used crime, housing, and employment data to create a comprehensive definition of what makes a neighborhood \"best.\" By combining these factors into a single metric, we were able to objectively compare neighborhoods across Pittsburgh.\n",
    "\n",
    "While the data identifies a clear \"best\" neighborhood, personal preferences may vary depending on individual priorities such as location, amenities, or lifestyle. However, this analysis demonstrates how data can be used to support more informed and objective decisions."
    "\n",
    "Housing Conclusion - Based on my housing metric, I found the best neighborhood with at least a population of 500 was Swisshelm Park. Housing data helps identify stable neighborhoods by highlighting occupancy, vacancy, and foreclosure trends. After filtering for populations over 500, the results are more reliable and less affected by small sample sizes. However, housing alone does not fully determine the “best” neighborhood, as other factors also matter.\n"
